ts of the war. The dissent of mountain folk reflected their own marginality in the face of rapidly increasing exploitation of timber resources by big firms, as well as partisan debates over loyalty. One of the few studies of the northern Appalachians, this book draws revealing parallels to the War in the southern mountains, exploring the roots of rural protest in frontier development, the market economy, military policy, partisan debate, and everyday resistance. Sandow also sheds new light on the party politics of rural resistance, rejecting easy depictions of war-opponents as traitors and malcontents for a more nuanced and complicated study of the class, economic upheaval, and localism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aAppalachians (People)zPennsylvaniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aAppalachians (People)zPennsylvaniaxPolitics and governmenty19th century. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / Civil War Period (1850-1877).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082323051840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823237562?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823237562423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823237562/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK